Plutzik's long poem with Walt Whitman, Federico García Lorca, and Hart Crane: "The train is moving through tunnels," Hirsch observes, "but the poet is also tunneling into himself. He moves above ground and struggles to surpass his own alienation to find something stable and permanent inside himself, a bright jewel that will outlast the instability of time."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican poetryxHistory and criticism. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 7aPOETRY / American / General.2bisacsh1 aHirsch, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Edward, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPlutzik, Hyam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamsey, Jarold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805432197?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805432197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805432197/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles